The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                          Wednesday , November 11 , 2009                                                                                                                                                                                                              
	 Guangzhou: Kavita Raut opened Indias account with a bronze in the womens 500m race on the first day of the 18th Asian Athletics Championships Tuesday. Kavita came up with a personal best effort of 16:05.19s to for the bronze. She bettered her earlier best of 16:13.17 she had clocked this season. Chinas Xue Fei won in 16:05.19 with Bahrains Chalchissa Tejitu Daba taking silver.         
	 Monte Carlo: Russian pole vaulter Yelena Isinbayeva leads the womens shortlist for the IAAF athlete of the year award the other contenders for which are Sanya Richards, Valerie Vili, Blanka Vlasic and Anita Wlodarczyk. The winners will be announced on Nov. 22.         
	 New Delhi: Prakash Amritraj and American partner Kevin Kim made a first round exit in the doubles event of the Knoxville ATP Challenger in the US after losing 2-6, 3-6 to Davey Sandgren and John-Patrick Smith.         
	 Bangalore: Billiards world champion Pankaj Advani Tuesday accepted the Eklavya award, the highest recognition for a sportsperson in Karnataka, two years after he turned down the honour accusing the state government of having a discriminatory attitude towards the sport.         
	 Windsor: Nick Faldo has been knighted by Queen Elizabeth II for a career in which he won six Majors and captained Europes Ryder Cup team.             
	 Zurich: Coach Diego Maradona will attend a disciplinary hearing, into his expletive-filled outburst following Argentinas qualification for the World Cup, at Fifa headquarters Sunday.       
